                <h2>3. Mendel's Monohybrid Cross (One Trait)</h2>
                <p>Pure Tall (TT) &times; Pure Short (tt).</p>
                <ol style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 25px 25px 25px 50px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #E2E8F0;">
                    <li><strong>Parent Generation (P):</strong> Pure Tall (TT) &times; Pure Short (tt).</li>
                    <li><strong>First Generation (F1):</strong> All offspring receive one 'T' and one 't' (Tt). Because 'T' is dominant, <span class="accent-blue">100% of F1 plants are TALL.</span> The short trait is hidden.</li>
                    <li><strong>Second Generation (F2):</strong> He self-pollinated the F1 plants (Tt &times; Tt).
                        <ul>
                            <li>The hidden short trait reappears! The final <em>Phenotypic Ratio</em> is <span class="exam-keyword">3 Tall : 1 Short</span>.</li>
                        </ul>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                <div class="ratta-box">
                    Monohybrid Cross F2 Ratio = <strong>3:1</strong>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>4. Mendel's Dihybrid Cross (Two Traits)</h2>
                <p>A cross focusing on TWO traits simultaneously. <br><em>Example: Round/Yellow seeds (RRYY) &times; Wrinkled/Green seeds (rryy).</em></p>
                
                <ul style="background: #F0F4F8; padding: 20px 20px 20px 40px; border-radius: 8px;">
                    <li><strong>F1 Generation:</strong> All seeds are Round and Yellow (RrYy).</li>
                    <li><strong>F2 Generation:</strong> New combinations appear! Some are Round/Green, some are Wrinkled/Yellow.</li>
                </ul>
                <div class="ratta-box">
                    Dihybrid Cross F2 Ratio = <strong>9:3:3:1</strong>
                </div>
                <div class="board-trap">
                    <strong>⚠️ Board Trap</strong>
                    The 9:3:3:1 ratio proves the <strong>Law of Independent Assortment</strong>. It means traits do not influence each other (a seed's shape does not dictate its color).
