        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>1. Plane Mirror Image Characteristics</h2>
                <p>Before diving into curved mirrors, you must know the 4 absolute properties of a flat (plane) mirror image:</p>
                <ol style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 20px 20px 20px 40px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #E2E8F0;">
                    <li><strong>Virtual and Erect:</strong> The image forms "behind" the mirror and is right-side up.</li>
                    <li><strong>Same Size:</strong> The image is exactly the same height as the object.</li>
                    <li><strong>Same Distance:</strong> The image forms as far behind the mirror as the object is in front of it.</li>
                    <li><strong>Laterally Inverted:</strong> The left side of the object appears as the right side of the image (why AMBULANCE is written backward!).</li>
                </ol>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>2. Rules for Lens Ray Diagrams</h2>
                <p>Lenses use Refraction (bending through glass). You must draw these accurately in the board exam:</p>
                <ul style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 20px 20px 20px 40px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #E2E8F0;">
                    <li><span class="accent-blue">Rule 1 (Parallel):</span> A ray parallel to the principal axis will pass through the principal Focus ($F_2$) on the other side.</li>
                    <li><span class="accent-blue">Rule 2 (Focus):</span> A ray passing through the Focus ($F_1$) will emerge parallel to the principal axis.</li>
                    <li><span class="accent">Rule 3 (Optical Center):</span> <br><strong>Crucial Board Exception:</strong> A ray of light passing through the exact Optical Center (O) of a lens goes completely straight and emerges without any deviation!</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>The Image Formation Cheat Sheet</h2>
                <table>
                    <tr><th>Device</th><th>Typical Image Formed</th><th>Special Case / Rule</th></tr>
                    <tr><td><strong>Concave Mirror</strong></td><td>Real & Inverted</td><td>Virtual & Erect ONLY if object is very close (between P and F).</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><strong>Convex Mirror</strong></td><td><span class="accent-blue">Always Virtual, Erect, Diminished</span></td><td>Used as rear-view mirrors (wider field of view).</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><strong>Convex Lens</strong></td><td>Real & Inverted</td><td>Virtual & Erect ONLY if object is very close (between O and F1).</td></tr>
                    <tr><td><strong>Concave Lens</strong></td><td><span class="accent-blue">Always Virtual, Erect, Diminished</span></td><td>Similar to a Convex Mirror.</td></tr>
                </table>
            </div>
