                        <th>Hypermetropia Correction Mechanics</th>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td>Image forms <strong>IN FRONT</strong> of the retina (eyeball too long).</td>
                        <td>Image forms <strong>BEHIND</strong> the retina (eyeball too short).</td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr>
                        <td><strong>Concave Lens:</strong> <span class="accent-blue">Diverges</span> light rays <em>before</em> they hit the eye lens. This pushes the focal point backward onto the retina.</td>
                        <td><strong>Convex Lens:</strong> <span class="accent-blue">Converges</span> light rays early. This accelerates focusing, pulling the focal point forward onto the retina.</td>
                    </tr>
                </table>
            </div>
        </div>

        <!-- SEQUENCER FOR RAINBOW -->
        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>3. Formation of a Rainbow <span class="punjabi">(ਸਤਰੰਗੀ ਪੀਂਘ)</span></h2>
                <p><strong>Interactive Sequencer:</strong> Build the process of a rainbow forming inside a water droplet.</p>
                <div class="sequencer-container" id="seq-ch10-1">
                    <div class="seq-step">
                        <strong>1. Refraction & Dispersion:</strong> Sunlight enters the water droplet, slows down, and splits into 7 colors.
                    </div>
                    <div class="seq-step">
                        <strong>2. Total Internal Reflection:</strong> The light hits the back wall of the water drop and bounces <em>inside</em> instead of passing through.
                    </div>
                    <div class="seq-step">
                        <strong>3. Refraction (Again):</strong> The colors exit the drop, reaching our eyes as a rainbow (always opposite to the sun).
                    </div>
                    <button class="seq-btn" onclick="revealNextStep('seq-ch10-1')">
