        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>Atmospheric Refraction: Why Planets Don't Twinkle</h2>
                <p>Stars twinkle due to <strong>Atmospheric Refraction</strong>. The atmosphere constantly shifts, bending starlight back and forth because stars are incredibly far away and act as tiny "point sources" of light.</p>
                <div style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 20px; border-radius: 12px; border-left: 5px solid var(--goku-primary); margin-top: 15px;">
                    <p><strong>So why don't planets twinkle?</strong></p>
                    <p>Planets are much closer to Earth. Instead of being a single point of light, they act as an <span class="exam-keyword">extended source</span> (a collection of many point sources). While one point of light on the planet might dim due to the atmosphere, another point gets brighter. These changes cancel each other out, resulting in a steady, non-twinkling shine.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>4. Scattering & The Tyndall Effect <span class="punjabi">(ਟਿੰਡਲ ਪ੍ਰਭਾਵ)</span></h2>
                <p><strong>Tyndall Effect:</strong> The scattering of a light beam by colloidal particles, making its path visible.</p>
                
                <h3>Atmospheric Phenomena</h3>
                <ul style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 20px 20px 20px 40px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #E2E8F0;">
                    <li><strong>Blue Sky:</strong> Fine air particles strongly scatter short wavelengths (blue) in all directions.</li>
                    <li><strong>Red Danger Signals:</strong> Red has the <span class="exam-keyword">longest wavelength</span>. It is scattered the <em>least</em> by fog, allowing it to reach our eyes directly over long distances.</li>
                    <li><strong>Space is Dark:</strong> In outer space, there is no atmosphere and no particles. Therefore, <strong>no scattering occurs</strong>.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

