                <h2>1. Ohm's Law & Reading a V-I Graph</h2>
                <div class="equation">V = I &times; R</div>
                <p>Ohm's law produces a linear graph when Voltage (V) is plotted against Current (I).</p>
                <ul style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 25px 25px 25px 50px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #E2E8F0;">
                    <li><span class="accent-blue">The Slope Formula:</span> In math, slope = $Y / X$. Therefore, the slope of a V-I graph is $V / I$.</li>
                    <li><span class="accent">Conclusion:</span> The slope of a V-I graph directly gives you the <strong>Resistance (R)</strong> of the conductor.</li>
                    <li><em>Exam Trick:</em> A steeper line (higher slope) means the wire has a higher resistance.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>2. Factors Affecting Resistance</h2>
                <div class="equation">R = &rho;L / A</div>
                <ul style="background: #F0F4F8; padding: 20px 20px 20px 40px; border-radius: 8px;">
                    <li><strong>Length (L):</strong> Resistance is <em>directly</em> proportional. A longer wire = more resistance.</li>
                    <li><strong>Area (A):</strong> Resistance is <em>inversely</em> proportional. A thicker wire = less resistance.</li>
                    <li><strong>Material (&rho;):</strong> Resistivity depends only on the material and temperature, NOT length.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

