                    <tr><td>Total $R = R_1 + R_2 + \dots$</td><td>$1/R = 1/R_1 + 1/R_2 + \dots$</td></tr>
                    <tr><td>Current (I) is the same everywhere.</td><td>Voltage (V) is the same everywhere.</td></tr>
                </table>
                <h3 style="margin-top:15px;">Why are Homes wired in Parallel?</h3>
                <p><span class="accent">1. The "All or Nothing" Flaw:</span> In series, if one appliance breaks, the whole house shuts off. <br><span class="accent">2. Shared Voltage:</span> In series, voltage divides. In parallel, every appliance gets the full 220V it needs.</p>
