                <h2>Joule's Law: Material Selection</h2>
                <p>When current passes through a high-resistance wire, electrical energy converts to heat ($H = I^2Rt$).</p>
                
                <ol style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 20px 20px 20px 40px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #E2E8F0;">
                    <li><strong>Why Tungsten for bulbs?</strong> It is a very strong metal with an incredibly high melting point (approx. $3380^\circ C$). It can get white-hot and emit light without melting.</li>
                    <li><strong>Why filled with gas?</strong> If a tungsten filament got that hot in normal air, oxygen would instantly burn (oxidize) it, snapping the wire. Bulbs are filled with chemically inactive gases like <span class="exam-keyword">Nitrogen</span> or <span class="exam-keyword">Argon</span> to prolong filament life.</li>
                </ol>
