        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>2. Field Patterns & Hand Rules</h2>
                <h3>Straight Wire</h3>
                <p>Forms <strong>concentric circles</strong>. Use the <span class="exam-keyword">Right-Hand Thumb Rule</span>: Point thumb in direction of current, fingers curl in direction of magnetic field.</p>
                
                <h3>Circular Loop</h3>
                <p>As you move to the center of the loop, the field lines become straight and parallel.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>3. Solenoids & Electromagnets</h2>
                <p>A <strong>Solenoid</strong> is a coil of many circular turns of insulated copper wire.</p>
                <ul style="background: #F8FAFC; padding: 20px 20px 20px 40px; border-radius: 12px; border: 1px solid #E2E8F0;">
                    <li><span class="accent-blue">Inside the Solenoid:</span> The field lines are parallel straight lines. This means the magnetic field is <strong>uniform (same everywhere)</strong> inside.</li>
                    <li><span class="accent">Electromagnet:</span> If you place a magnetic material (like <em>soft iron</em>) inside the coil, the strong field magnetizes it. This creates a powerful, temporary magnet!</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
            <div class="content-box">
                <h2>4. Force on a Conductor & Fleming's LHR</h2>
                <p>Putting a current-carrying wire inside an external magnetic field creates a physical <strong>FORCE</strong> pushing the wire. (This is how motors work!).</p>
                
                <div class="board-trap">
                    <strong>⚠️ Board Trap</strong>
                    The force is maximum when the wire is placed strictly <strong>perpendicular ($90^\circ$)</strong> to the magnetic field. Force is ZERO if placed parallel!
                </div>
                
                <h3 style="margin-top:20px;">Fleming's Left-Hand Rule</h3>
                <p>Stretch thumb, forefinger, and middle finger at right angles: <strong>F</strong>orefinger = Magnetic <strong>F</strong>ield, <strong>C</strong>enter finger = <strong>C</strong>urrent, <strong>Thumb</strong> = <strong>Thrust/Motion</strong>.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
